{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"822351f3-c87d-48ba-a151-4331ca2642eb","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector via **npx**:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`) that acts as an MCP client. It will spawn your server as a child process using stdio.\n\n**From the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse discovered **tools**, **resources**, and **prompts**\n- Invoke tools with custom input and see JSON responses\n- View the raw JSON-RPC message exchange for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs/diagnostics to **stderr** — any non-JSON on stdout breaks the protocol.\n- Pass environment variables with `-e KEY=VALUE` before the command.\n- If your server needs arguments: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./Server.csproj -- --my-flag`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3427daf2-79b1-4fd3-be79-e3e2279a9bc7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code change request. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":305,"requestId":"E044:D8BCE:11265A0:128A51E:69E74F7B"},"id":"dd91258e-fb81-4b06-bcf5-a1b3958edaa0","timestamp":"2026-04-21T10:20:58.043Z","parentId":"1e37e08f-b231-42ed-af61-20ba1db67fbe"}
